"Tsonis A.A., Hunt A.G., Elsner J.B.","On the relation between ENSO and global climate change",2003,"Meteorology and Atmospheric Physics","84","3-4",,"229","242",,,10.1007/s00703-003-0001-7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0346905481&partnerID=40&md5=e2e21c9af3107a66291d458a8fc58084","Department of Mathematical Sciences, Atmospheric Sciences Group, University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee, Milwaukee, WI 53201-0413, United States; CIRES, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309, United States; Department of Geography, Florida State University, Tallahasse, FL 32306, United States","Tsonis, A.A., Department of Mathematical Sciences, Atmospheric Sciences Group, University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee, Milwaukee, WI 53201-0413, United States; Hunt, A.G., CIRES, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309, United States; Elsner, J.B., Department of Geography, Florida State University, Tallahasse, FL 32306, United States","Two lines of research into climate change and El Nino/ Southern Oscillation (ENSO) converge on the conclusion that changes in ENSO statistics occur as a response to global climate (temperature) fluctuations. One approach focuses on the statistics of temperature fluctuations interpreted within the framework of random walks. The second is based on the discovery of correlation between the recurrence frequency of El Nino and temperature change, while developing physical arguments to explain several phenomena associated with changes in El Nino frequency. Consideration of both perspectives leads to greater confidence in, and guidance for, the physical interpretation of the relationship between ENSO and global climate change. Topics considered include global dynamics of ENSO, ENSO triggers, and climate prediction and predictability.",,"climate change; El Nino-Southern Oscillation; global climate; oceanic circulation; temperature effect",,,,,,"Anderson, D.M., Long-term changes in the frequency of occurrence of El Niño events (1992) El Niño: Historical and P